Ah! Now I see exactly what’s confusing you — yes, in textbooks, present simple is often described as being used for general truths, habits, routines, facts, but that’s not the whole story. Let me clarify carefully.

Present Simple Uses

The present simple is used for:

=> Habits / routines / repeated actions

I drink coffee every morning.

She walks to school.

=> General truths / facts / laws of nature

Water boils at 100°C.

The sun rises in the east.

=> States / conditions (stative verbs)

I know the answer.

She likes chocolate.

=> Instructions or directions

You turn left at the corner.

Add sugar to the mixture.

=> Scheduled events in the near future


| Feature   | Don’t go there                       | You shouldn’t go there    |
| --------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------- |
| Verb Type | Imperative (present simple negative) | Modal verb (should + not) |
| Tone      | Strong, commanding                   | Polite, advisory          |
| Meaning   | Immediate order / prohibition        | Advice / suggestion       |
| Subject   | Implied “you”                        | Explicit “you”            |


The train leaves at 6 PM.

=> Imperative sentences / commands (negative or positive)

Sit down.

Don’t touch that! ✅ ← this is where your sentence fits

Don’t touch that! ✅ ← this is where your sentence fits
